1
00:02:41,719 --> 00:02:43,644
[Computer beeping]

2
00:04:57,978 --> 00:05:00,173
LEADER:
Bio-readouts are in the green.

3
00:05:00,213 --> 00:05:01,703
Looks like she's alive.

4
00:05:05,185 --> 00:05:07,483
There goes our salvage, guys.

5
00:05:34,681 --> 00:05:36,148
MED-TECH: How are we today?

6
00:05:36,183 --> 00:05:38,151
RIPLEY: Oh. Terrible.

7
00:05:38,185 --> 00:05:40,415
MED-TECH:
Better than yesterday, at least.

8
00:05:40,454 --> 00:05:41,853
Where am I?

9
00:05:41,888 --> 00:05:43,082
MED-TECH: You're safe.

10
00:05:43,123 --> 00:05:46,149
You're at Gateway Station.
Been here a couple of days.

11
00:05:46,193 --> 00:05:49,651
You were pretty groggy at first,
but now you're OK.

12
00:05:49,696 --> 00:05:51,857
Looks like you've got a visitor.

13
00:05:54,334 --> 00:05:56,632
Jonesy! Come here!

14
00:05:56,670 --> 00:05:58,968
Hey, come here.

15
00:05:59,006 --> 00:06:01,668
How are you, you stupid cat?

16
00:06:01,708 --> 00:06:03,403
How are you?

17
00:06:03,443 --> 00:06:05,411
Where have you been?

18
00:06:05,445 --> 00:06:08,414
BURKE:
Guess you two have met, huh?

19
00:06:08,448 --> 00:06:11,849
I'm Carter Burke.
I work for the Company.

20
00:06:11,885 --> 00:06:14,877
Don't let that fool you.
I'm really an OK guy.

21
00:06:16,223 --> 00:06:18,157
I'm glad you're feeling better.

22
00:06:18,191 --> 00:06:22,150
They tell me the weakness and
disorientation should pass soon.

23
00:06:22,195 --> 00:06:24,322
That's just
natural side effects...

24
00:06:24,364 --> 00:06:27,765
of such an unusually long
hypersleep.

25
00:06:27,801 --> 00:06:30,133
What do you mean?

26
00:06:30,170 --> 00:06:32,502
How long was I out there?

27
00:06:34,174 --> 00:06:36,301
Has no one discussed this
with you?

28
00:06:36,343 --> 00:06:37,810
No.

29
00:06:37,844 --> 00:06:43,077
But, I mean,
I don't recognize this place.

30
00:06:43,116 --> 00:06:46,142
No, I know. Uh... OK.

31
00:06:46,186 --> 00:06:49,121
This might be a shock.
It's long...

32
00:06:49,156 --> 00:06:51,124
How long?

33
00:06:51,158 --> 00:06:52,853
Please.

34
00:06:54,661 --> 00:06:56,288
Fifty-seven years.

35
00:06:57,497 --> 00:06:58,623
What?

36
00:06:58,665 --> 00:07:02,999
BURKE: You were out there
for fifty-seven years.

37
00:07:03,036 --> 00:07:06,369
You drifted
right through the core systems.

38
00:07:06,406 --> 00:07:09,102
It's really just blind luck...

39
00:07:09,142 --> 00:07:12,407
that a deep-salvage team
found you.

40
00:07:12,446 --> 00:07:14,607
It's one in a thousand, really.

41
00:07:14,648 --> 00:07:16,912
You're damn lucky
to be alive, kiddo.

42
00:07:16,950 --> 00:07:18,747
You could be floating
out there forever.

43
00:07:20,787 --> 00:07:21,981
You OK?

44
00:07:22,889 --> 00:07:24,049
[Hiss]

45
00:07:24,091 --> 00:07:25,058
Oh.

46
00:07:25,092 --> 00:07:28,186
[Heartbeat]

47
00:07:29,429 --> 00:07:32,296
- [Hiss]
- Oh!

48
00:07:32,332 --> 00:07:33,560
BURKE: You OK?

49
00:07:39,072 --> 00:07:40,198
[Hiss]

50
00:07:40,240 --> 00:07:41,935
Oh!

51
00:07:41,975 --> 00:07:43,909
God!

52
00:07:45,378 --> 00:07:47,471
BURKE: Nurse! Please!

53
00:07:48,982 --> 00:07:50,916
Someone get in here now!

54
00:07:50,951 --> 00:07:52,316
RIPLEY: No!

55
00:07:52,352 --> 00:07:54,081
BURKE: Now!

56
00:07:54,121 --> 00:07:56,351
- Hold...
- Please.

57
00:07:56,389 --> 00:07:58,687
DOCTOR: Hold her.

58
00:07:58,725 --> 00:08:00,693
Kill me!

59
00:08:08,935 --> 00:08:10,266
No!

60
00:08:10,303 --> 00:08:11,497
No!

61
00:08:17,944 --> 00:08:19,639
MED-TECH: Bad dreams again?

62
00:08:19,679 --> 00:08:21,271
You want something
to help you sleep?

63
00:08:21,314 --> 00:08:22,645
No.

64
00:08:24,151 --> 00:08:25,675
I've slept enough.

65
00:08:27,487 --> 00:08:28,920
Jonesy.

66
00:08:28,955 --> 00:08:30,422
Come here.

67
00:08:30,457 --> 00:08:31,947
[Meow]

68
00:08:31,992 --> 00:08:33,550
Shh.

69
00:08:37,964 --> 00:08:39,261
It's all right.

70
00:08:41,067 --> 00:08:42,466
It's all right now.

71
00:08:44,971 --> 00:08:46,962
It's over.

72
00:08:49,176 --> 00:08:51,167
[Birds chirping]

73
00:09:05,792 --> 00:09:07,783
[Chirping stops]

74
00:09:12,132 --> 00:09:15,067
BURKE: Hi. Sorry I'm late.
Been running behind all morning.

75
00:09:15,101 --> 00:09:17,001
RIPLEY: ls there
any word about my daughter?

76
00:09:18,004 --> 00:09:21,599
Uh... I think we should
worry about the hearing now.

77
00:09:21,641 --> 00:09:23,108
We don't have a lot of time.

78
00:09:23,143 --> 00:09:25,111
I read your deposition,
and it's great.

79
00:09:25,145 --> 00:09:26,874
If you stick to that,
we'll be fine.

80
00:09:26,913 --> 00:09:30,110
The thing is, there are gonna be
a lot of heavyweights in there.

81
00:09:30,150 --> 00:09:32,180
Feds, Interstellar
Commerce Commission...

82
00:09:32,313 --> 00:09:35,146
Colonial Administration,
insurance company guys.

83
00:09:35,183 --> 00:09:37,947
Do you have any news
about my daughter?

84
00:09:39,120 --> 00:09:41,315
We did come up
with some information.

85
00:09:41,356 --> 00:09:43,586
Why don't we sit down?

86
00:09:43,624 --> 00:09:46,593
I was hoping to wait
until after the inquest.

87
00:09:46,627 --> 00:09:48,117
Uh...

88
00:09:50,631 --> 00:09:52,758
"Amanda Ripley McClaren..."

89
00:09:52,800 --> 00:09:54,768
married name, I guess...

90
00:09:54,802 --> 00:09:56,599
"age sixty-six."

91
00:09:56,637 --> 00:09:59,606
That was at the time
of her death...

92
00:10:00,908 --> 00:10:03,468
which was two years ago.

93
00:10:05,146 --> 00:10:07,137
I'm real sorry.

94
00:10:17,191 --> 00:10:18,351
Amy.

95
00:10:21,162 --> 00:10:23,130
BURKE:
She was cremated and interred...

96
00:10:23,164 --> 00:10:26,133
at Westlake Repository,
Little Chute, Wisconsin.

97
00:10:26,167 --> 00:10:27,828
No children. I checked.

98
00:10:33,508 --> 00:10:36,136
I promised her...

99
00:10:36,177 --> 00:10:38,668
that I would be home
for her birthday.

100
00:10:41,682 --> 00:10:44,344
Her eleventh birthday.

101
00:10:48,022 --> 00:10:49,649
Ohh...

102
00:10:49,757 --> 00:10:53,318
INVESTIGATOR: I'd like to
go back to this point...

103
00:10:53,361 --> 00:10:55,386
about the override
destruct elements.

104
00:10:55,430 --> 00:10:57,193
I don't understand this.

105
00:10:57,231 --> 00:11:00,394
We have been here
three and a half hours.

106
00:11:00,435 --> 00:11:03,996
How many different ways
do you want the same story?

107
00:11:04,038 --> 00:11:07,474
VAN LEUWEN: Look at it
from our perspective, please.

108
00:11:08,676 --> 00:11:10,303
Please?

109
00:11:12,647 --> 00:11:15,844
You freely admit to
detonating the engines of...

110
00:11:15,883 --> 00:11:18,784
and thereby destroying
an M-Class star freighter...

111
00:11:18,820 --> 00:11:21,288
a rather expensive piece
of hardware.

112
00:11:21,322 --> 00:11:23,790
INVESTIGATOR: Forty-two million
in adjusted dollars.

113
00:11:23,825 --> 00:11:26,794
That's minus payload, of course.

114
00:11:26,828 --> 00:11:28,796
VAN LEUWEN: The lifeboat's
flight recorder...

115
00:11:28,830 --> 00:11:31,799
corroborates some elements
of your account...

116
00:11:31,833 --> 00:11:33,801
in that, for reasons unknown...

117
00:11:33,835 --> 00:11:36,633
the Nostromo
set down on LV-426...

118
00:11:36,671 --> 00:11:39,299
an unsurveyed planet
at that time...

119
00:11:39,340 --> 00:11:41,308
that it resumed its course...

120
00:11:41,342 --> 00:11:45,039
and was subsequently set
for self-destruct by you...

121
00:11:45,079 --> 00:11:46,307
for reasons unknown.

122
00:11:46,347 --> 00:11:47,644
Not for reasons unknown.

123
00:11:47,682 --> 00:11:48,910
I told you.

124
00:11:48,950 --> 00:11:52,215
We set down on Company orders
to get this thing...

125
00:11:52,253 --> 00:11:57,384
which destroyed my crew
and your expensive ship.

126
00:11:57,425 --> 00:11:58,585
The analysis team...

127
00:11:58,626 --> 00:12:01,151
which went over the lifeboat
centimeter by centimeter...

128
00:12:01,195 --> 00:12:03,891
found no physical evidence
of the creature you describe.

129
00:12:03,931 --> 00:12:08,129
Good! That's because I blew it
out of the goddamn air lock.

130
00:12:09,804 --> 00:12:11,169
Like I said.

131
00:12:13,708 --> 00:12:15,369
INVESTIGATOR:
Are there any species...

132
00:12:15,409 --> 00:12:18,139
like this hostile organism
on LV-426?

133
00:12:18,179 --> 00:12:21,114
ECA REP: No. It's a rock.
No indigenous life.

134
00:12:22,917 --> 00:12:26,444
Did IQs just drop sharply
while I was away?

135
00:12:26,487 --> 00:12:29,115
Ma'am, I already said
it was not indigenous.

136
00:12:29,157 --> 00:12:32,024
It was a derelict spacecraft.
It was an alien ship.

137
00:12:32,059 --> 00:12:33,651
It was not from there.

138
00:12:33,694 --> 00:12:36,686
Do you get it?
We homed in on its beacon.

139
00:12:36,731 --> 00:12:39,632
And found something
never recorded once...

140
00:12:39,667 --> 00:12:42,659
in over three hundred
surveyed worlds.

141
00:12:42,703 --> 00:12:48,005
"A creature that gestates
inside a living human host."

142
00:12:48,042 --> 00:12:49,703
These are your words.

143
00:12:49,744 --> 00:12:51,905
"And has concentrated acid
for blood."

144
00:12:51,946 --> 00:12:53,038
RIPLEY: That's right.

145
00:12:54,248 --> 00:12:58,014
Look.
I can see where this is going...

146
00:12:58,052 --> 00:13:00,680
but I'm telling you
that those things exist.

147
00:13:00,721 --> 00:13:02,746
Thank you, Officer Ripley.
That will be all.

148
00:13:02,790 --> 00:13:04,155
Please! You're not listening.

149
00:13:04,192 --> 00:13:05,750
Kane... the crew member...

150
00:13:05,793 --> 00:13:10,628
Kane, who went into that ship,
said he saw thousands of eggs.

151
00:13:10,665 --> 00:13:12,724
Thank you. That will be all.

152
00:13:12,767 --> 00:13:14,860
God damn it, that's not all!

153
00:13:14,902 --> 00:13:17,632
If one of those things gets
down here, that will be all!

154
00:13:17,672 --> 00:13:21,039
And all this bullshit
you think is important...

155
00:13:21,075 --> 00:13:23,407
you can kiss all that good-bye!

156
00:13:29,617 --> 00:13:33,246
It is the finding
of this court of inquiry...

157
00:13:33,287 --> 00:13:35,380
that Warrant Officer
E. Ripley...

158
00:13:35,423 --> 00:13:38,290
N-O-C-one-four-four-seven-two...

159
00:13:38,326 --> 00:13:41,420
has acted
with questionable judgment...

160
00:13:41,462 --> 00:13:44,488
and is unfit
to hold an ICC license...

161
00:13:44,532 --> 00:13:47,433
as a commercial flight officer.

162
00:13:47,468 --> 00:13:51,029
Said license is hereby
suspended indefinitely.

163
00:13:52,206 --> 00:13:54,174
No criminal charges...

164
00:13:54,208 --> 00:13:57,177
will be filed against you
at this time...

165
00:13:57,211 --> 00:13:59,645
and you are released
on your own recognizance...

166
00:13:59,680 --> 00:14:02,444
for a six-month period
of psychometric probation...

167
00:14:02,483 --> 00:14:07,716
to include monthly review by
an ICC psychiatric technician.

168
00:14:09,790 --> 00:14:12,623
These proceedings are closed.

169
00:14:23,504 --> 00:14:25,472
BURKE:
That could have been better.

170
00:14:25,506 --> 00:14:26,973
Look, I think... Ripley.

171
00:14:27,008 --> 00:14:28,976
RIPLEY: Van Leuwen.

172
00:14:29,010 --> 00:14:31,979
Why don't you just
check out LV-426?

173
00:14:32,013 --> 00:14:33,981
VAN LEUWEN:
Because I don't have to.

174
00:14:34,015 --> 00:14:36,643
People have been there
for over twenty years...

175
00:14:36,684 --> 00:14:39,175
and they never complained
about any hostile organism.

176
00:14:39,220 --> 00:14:41,188
RIPLEY: What people?

177
00:14:41,222 --> 00:14:42,883
VAN LEUWEN: Terraformers.

178
00:14:42,923 --> 00:14:44,220
Planet engineers.

179
00:14:44,258 --> 00:14:46,624
They go in,
set up atmosphere processors...

180
00:14:46,661 --> 00:14:48,390
to make the air breathable.

181
00:14:48,429 --> 00:14:50,397
It takes decades.

182
00:14:50,431 --> 00:14:53,059
It's what we call
a shake 'n' bake colony.

183
00:14:53,100 --> 00:14:56,729
How many are there?
How many colonists?

184
00:14:56,771 --> 00:15:00,138
I don't know.
Sixty, maybe seventy families.

185
00:15:00,174 --> 00:15:01,334
Do you mind?

186
00:15:03,644 --> 00:15:05,134
Families.

187
00:15:08,082 --> 00:15:09,572
Jesus.

188
00:15:34,133 --> 00:15:36,124
[Honk honk]

189
00:16:25,117 --> 00:16:27,085
AL: l'll be down in maintenance.

190
00:16:27,119 --> 00:16:29,087
- AI?
- What?

191
00:16:29,121 --> 00:16:30,679
- Hey, Al.
- What?

192
00:16:30,722 --> 00:16:32,587
LYDECKER: Remember you sent
some wildcatters...

193
00:16:32,624 --> 00:16:33,852
out in the middle of nowhere
last week...

194
00:16:33,892 --> 00:16:36,190
out past the llium Range?

195
00:16:36,228 --> 00:16:39,459
One's on the horn,
a mom-and-pop survey team.

196
00:16:39,498 --> 00:16:41,864
He's onto something,
wants his claim honored.

197
00:16:41,900 --> 00:16:43,834
AL:
Why wouldn't it be honored?

198
00:16:43,869 --> 00:16:47,930
LYDECKER: Because you sent them
on Company orders maybe?

199
00:16:47,973 --> 00:16:51,067
AL: Christ. Some haunch in
a cushy office on Earth says...

200
00:16:51,110 --> 00:16:53,010
"Go look at a grid reference."

201
00:16:53,045 --> 00:16:56,310
We look. They don't say why,
and I don't ask...

202
00:16:56,348 --> 00:16:59,613
because it takes two weeks
to get an answer out here.

203
00:16:59,651 --> 00:17:01,619
The answer is always,
"Don't ask."

204
00:17:01,653 --> 00:17:04,087
LYDECKER:
What do I tell this guy?

205
00:17:04,123 --> 00:17:08,150
AL: As far as I'm concerned,
if he finds something, it's his.

206
00:17:08,193 --> 00:17:09,626
- Lydecker?
- What?

207
00:17:10,963 --> 00:17:12,658
LYDECKER: You kids know
you're not supposed to be here!

208
00:17:12,698 --> 00:17:13,926
Get out!

209
00:17:46,665 --> 00:17:49,099
TIMMY:
You go in places we can't fit.

210
00:17:49,134 --> 00:17:52,069
NEWT:
So? That's why I'm the best!

211
00:17:52,104 --> 00:17:53,503
MOTHER: Knock it off.

212
00:17:53,539 --> 00:17:56,838
If I catch you playing in the
air ducts, l'll tan your hides.

213
00:17:56,875 --> 00:17:59,139
NEWT: Mom, all the kids play...

214
00:17:59,178 --> 00:18:01,738
FATHER: Wait.
Have a look at this.

215
00:18:12,090 --> 00:18:15,423
Folks,
we have scored big this time.

216
00:18:21,533 --> 00:18:23,364
What is it, Dad?

217
00:18:27,973 --> 00:18:29,270
I'm not sure.

218
00:18:31,043 --> 00:18:33,068
Let's see if we can't get
a closer look at this thing...

219
00:18:33,111 --> 00:18:35,079
maybe through that crack
on the side.

220
00:18:35,113 --> 00:18:36,603
MOTHER: Shouldn't we call in?

221
00:18:36,648 --> 00:18:39,082
Let's wait till we know
what to call it in as.

222
00:18:43,121 --> 00:18:45,146
That's about as close
as we can get.

223
00:18:46,158 --> 00:18:47,819
Should we look inside?

224
00:19:02,774 --> 00:19:05,743
MOTHER: You kids stay inside.
I mean it.

225
00:19:05,777 --> 00:19:07,267
We'll be right back.

226
00:19:07,312 --> 00:19:09,143
- TIMMY: OK.
- NEWT: Bye.

227
00:20:25,190 --> 00:20:26,885
TIMMY: Huh?

228
00:20:26,925 --> 00:20:30,156
NEWT: Timmy,
they've been gone a long time.

229
00:20:30,195 --> 00:20:33,255
TIMMY: lt'll be OK.
Dad knows what he's doing.

230
00:20:34,333 --> 00:20:35,800
MOTHER: Mayday! Mayday!

231
00:20:35,834 --> 00:20:38,735
This is Alpha Kilo Two-four-
niner calling Control!

232
00:20:38,770 --> 00:20:41,796
This is
Alpha Kilo Two-four-niner!

233
00:20:41,840 --> 00:20:46,209
NEWT: Aah!

234
00:20:47,212 --> 00:20:51,672
Aah!

235
00:21:13,538 --> 00:21:16,166
[Meow meow]

236
00:21:21,446 --> 00:21:23,346
[Doorbell beeps]

237
00:21:27,652 --> 00:21:28,812
BURKE: Hiya, Ripley.

238
00:21:28,854 --> 00:21:31,982
This is Lieutenant Gorman
of the Colonial Marine Corps...

239
00:21:33,158 --> 00:21:35,319
Ripley, we have to talk.

240
00:21:35,360 --> 00:21:38,989
We've lost contact
with the colony on LV-426.

241
00:21:45,937 --> 00:21:47,837
I don't believe this.

242
00:21:47,873 --> 00:21:50,341
You guys throw me
to the wolves...

243
00:21:50,375 --> 00:21:52,741
and now you want me
to go back there?

244
00:21:52,778 --> 00:21:55,474
Forget it.
It's not my problem.

245
00:21:55,514 --> 00:21:56,947
- Can I finish?
- No.

246
00:21:56,982 --> 00:21:58,574
There's no way.

247
00:22:00,118 --> 00:22:02,450
GORMAN: You wouldn't be
going in with the troops.

248
00:22:02,487 --> 00:22:05,081
I can guarantee your safety.

249
00:22:05,123 --> 00:22:07,921
BURKE: These Colonial Marines
are very tough hombres.

250
00:22:07,959 --> 00:22:10,621
They're packing
state-of-the-art firepower.

251
00:22:10,662 --> 00:22:13,061
There's nothing
they can't handle.

252
00:22:13,194 --> 00:22:14,286
Lieutenant, am I right?

253
00:22:14,329 --> 00:22:18,060
We've been trained to deal
with situations like this.

254
00:22:18,099 --> 00:22:21,296
Then you don't need me.
I'm not a soldier.

255
00:22:21,336 --> 00:22:24,066
BURKE: But we don't know
exactly what's going on.

256
00:22:24,105 --> 00:22:25,902
It may be a downed transmitter.

257
00:22:25,940 --> 00:22:28,204
